The taxonomic affinity of
Coryssiphus
is problematic. First of all, Liocranidae , the family in which the genus is presently placed, is poorly defined (
), since not a single synapomorphy has been found for it so far (
). Moreover, recent work suggests that Liocranidae , as currently composed, may not be monophyletic (
;
;
;
, Wheeler et al . 2016). At least, Liocranidae seems to be divided into a group centred around
Liocranum L. Koch, 1866
, whose members have an oblique median tapetum (
) and obliquely depressed endites (
, figs 8, 10;
;
), and a group centred around
Agroeca Westring, 1861
, whose members lack these features (
, Domènech et al . in press).
Coryssiphus
differs strongly from the
Liocranum
-group by the absence of an oblique tapetum in the PME ( Fig. 3D ), the absence of ventrolateral erectile bristles on the anterior legs, and the absence of an oblique depression and lateral notch of the endites. It also differs from the
Agroeca
-group by its simple circular bulbus without C, MA or additional tegular apophyses. In contrast,
Coryssiphus
has non-depressed endites with a marked thin, diagonal groove ( Fig. 3F ), as in
Xantharia Deeleman-Reinhold, 2001
(
: fig. 258), AME slightly larger than ALE, ALS separated, relatively large PLS with a long, conical apical segment, a simple subcircular bulbus with a long, sickle-shaped basally implanted E, a hook-shaped RTA (although rarely bifid or inconspicuous in some Systariinae), and a vulva with short ID, all characters that are found in Miturgidae : Systariinae, as defined in
. The similarity between the male palps of
Coryssiphus
and
Systaria elberti (Strand, 1913)
for example, is striking (
: fig. 239;
).
Coryssiphus
is herewith tentatively transferred to Miturgidae : Systariinae, as presently constituted (
).
